pecification includes an API to render text on a canvas.<br/><br/>-Ben Galbraith (re: Bespin)</blockquote>\nOn the one hand, I&#8217;m disappointed, as the text rendering was too me the most impressive part of Bespin. Â On the other, that&#8217;s a really cool feature to have in HTML 5.\r\n                    </div>\r\n                \r\n                \r\n                \r\n                \r\n                \r\n                \r\n                \r\n                \r\n                \r\n                \r\n                \r\n            </div>\r\n        \r\n            \r\n                <div class=\"date\">\r\n                    Feb 13\r\n                </div>\r\n            \r\n        \r\n            <div class=\"post\">\r\n                <a href=\"http://www.kylemaxwell.com/post/78092894/plotting-my-productivity\"><img src=\"/themes/4/link.gif\" \r\n                class=\"permalink\" alt=\"Permalink\"/></a>\r\n\r\n                \r\n                    <div class=\"regular\">\r\n                        <h2><a href=\"http://www.kylemaxwell.com/post/78092894/plotting-my-productivity\">Plotting my productivity</a></h2>\r\n                        <p>I think of it as roughly the amount of changes I can make to my code. Â  I can get that from my Git history like so&#8230;</p>\n<p>$: git log &#8212;numstat -w &#8212;summary &#8212;date=iso &#8212;diff-filter=M</p>\n<p>This grabs only non-whitespace modifications to text files, and outputs them in an easily parsable format. Â Here&#8217;s a quick Ruby script to transform the output of that Git command to the line-per-commit format: &lt;UNIXTIME&gt;&lt;TAB&gt;&lt;ADDED&gt;&lt;TAB&gt;&lt;DELETED&gt;.</p>\n<p>\n<script src=\"http://gist.github.com/64054.js\"></script></p>\n<p>Then, we can push this into Gnuplot (apt-get/port install gnuplot). Â I&#8217;d also consider changing the plot styles, and binning the commits by hour. Â In the future, I plan on developing this, and possibly correlating it with my bug/issue tracker.</p>\n<p>$:Â git log &#8212;numstat -w &#8212;summary &#8212;date=iso &#8212;diff-filter=M | ruby transform.rb &gt; out.txt<br/>$: gnuplot &lt; plotter.txtÂ </p>\n<p>\n<script src=\"http://gist.github.com/64055.js\"></script></p>\n<p>The output looks like this (deleted lines in red, added in green):</p>\n<p><img src=\"http://20.media.tumblr.com/jO8KVUSqLjwt4ktu29F78lTVo1_500.gif\"/></p>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                \r\n                \r\n                \r\n                \r\n                \r\n                \r\n                \r\n                \r\n                \r\n                \r\n                \r\n            </div>\r\n        \r\n            \r\n                <div class=\"date\">\r\n                    Feb 05\r\n                </div>\r\n            \r\n        \r\n            <div class=\"post\">\r\n                <a href=\"http://www.kylemaxwell.com/post/75947823/too-many-opinions\"><img src=\"/themes/4/link.gif\" \r\n                class=\"permalink\" alt=\"Permalink\"/></a>\r\n\r\n                \r\n                    <div class=\"regular\">\r\n                        <h2><a href=\"http://www.kylemaxwell.com/post/75947823/too-many-opinions\">Too many opinions</a></h2>\r\n                        After a year&#8217;s hiatus, it&#8217;s time to start blogging again. Â I need a place to express some of the ideas I have floating around. Â I&#8217;ll have links to some of my projects here soon.\r\n                    </div>\r\n                \r\n                \r\n                \r\n                \r\n                \r\n                \r\n                \r\n                \r\n                \r\n                \r\n                \r\n            </div>\r\n        \r\n            \r\n                <div class=\"date\">\r\n                    Apr 23\r\n                </div>\r\n            \r\n        \r\n            <div class=\"post\">\r\n                <a href=\"http://www.kylemaxwell.com/post/1