>10/25/2008</em>\n			</div>\n\n			<p class=\"review_comment ieSucks\">I have to admit, i&#39;ve seen some terrible shows at Amnesia, but also some great ones. Tonight was a great one. There was a Burlesque Belly Dance show with--I&#39;m not exaggerating--the most entertaining belly dance that I have ever seen. I don&#39;t remember the name of the different dancers and their groups, but two of them danced with Ultra Gypsy. (You can check them out on youtube.) They were great. Their movement was technically skilled, insanely sensual, a true worship of &nbsp;the feminine divine. It was inspiring. All the women were HOT! It was a really fun night out. I love the city. I should also mention that even though it is not yet halloween, a number of the patrons were decked out in edwardian dress, cabaret outfits, pirate costumes, and other hilarious and/or beautiful clothes. It was truly festive. Great people watching.<br /><br />This venue is small, so be prepared for an intimate setting. The vibe is usually friendly. Drinks are not great. Sound system is just okay. The real reason to go to Amnesia is that because it is such a small venue, they can afford to take chances on new bands and eclectic shows like this one and still sell enough tickets and drinks to stay open. This is one of the things I love most about the nightclub and music scene in SF; it is not overly commercial and jaded. People still self-produce and self-distribute here. And there is a child-like glee with which people perform all kinds of different things--electric hula hooping in the park at night, random performance art pieces, guerrilla theatre, belly dance, roller derby, puppet theatre. I LOVE SF!</p> 			\n		\n		\n			<p class=\"externalReviewActions\">\n				<a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"/signup\" class=\"bookmark\" rel=\"AWIyI3OgwHhEDpMRb8lOzA\" title=\"Something catch your eye?<br> Bookmark this business to build your own list of fun ideas to check out later!\" onclick=\"initBookSignUp(this,\'wm5_P-pfEwYw